    {
      "turn_number": 28,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I pictured us as a team — him coming home from work, taking the older kids, changing diapers, making dinner while I tried to rest and heal. I imagined late-night whispers over the baby monitor, the two of us trading smiles and small moments of normalcy. I needed him to be calm, steady, and present — especially with my pre-eclampsia making every appointment scary.\n\nThe truth has been messier. He’s tried — he stayed the night at the hospital once, brought me coffee, sat with me while they watched my blood pressure — and those moments meant everything. But work and our tight money situation pull him away. He’s exhausted, sometimes short-tempered, and we snap at each other over little things. Caregiving gets shared more on practical tasks than emotional labor; I still carry most of the worry. Intimacy feels distant; fear and fatigue eat up the space where closeness used to be. We’re figuring it out, but some days I feel very alone even when he’s in the same room.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V4_POST_Q07",
      "input_tokens": 1397,
      "output_tokens": 476
    },
